# MongoDB Environment Variables

## Local Development (`.env` file)

```env
# MongoDB Connection
MONGODB_URI=mongodb://localhost:27017/study-buddy

# Server
PORT=3000
NODE_ENV=development

# Session
SESSION_SECRET=your-session-secret-here

# CORS (if needed)
CORS_ORIGIN=http://localhost:3000
```

## Railway Deployment

When deploying to Railway, set these environment variables in Railway dashboard:

```env
MONGODB_URI=mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster0.xxxxx.mongodb.net/study-buddy
NODE_ENV=production
PORT=8080
SESSION_SECRET=generate-a-random-secret-here
```

## Vercel Deployment

Add to Vercel Environment Variables:

```env
MONGODB_URI=mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster0.xxxxx.mongodb.net/study-buddy
NODE_ENV=production
SESSION_SECRET=generate-a-random-secret-here
```

---

## Getting MongoDB Connection String

### Option 1: MongoDB Atlas (Cloud MongoDB)

1. Go to https://www.mongodb.com/cloud/atlas
2. Create free account
3. Create project
4. Build database cluster
5. Click "Connect"
6. Get connection string: `mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster.mongodb.net/study-buddy`

### Option 2: Local MongoDB

1. Install MongoDB locally
2. Start MongoDB service
3. Use: `mongodb://localhost:27017/study-buddy`

### Option 3: MongoDB Community Cloud

Similar to Atlas - cloud-hosted MongoDB

---

## How to Use MongoDB Connection Strings

### In Code
```javascript
process.env.MONGODB_URI // Already configured to use .env
```

### In .env file
```env
MONGODB_URI=mongodb+srv://user:pass@cluster.mongodb.net/database
```

### In Railway Dashboard
1. Go to your Railway project
2. Select "Variables"
3. Add new variable
4. Name: `MONGODB_URI`
5. Value: your connection string
6. Save

### In Vercel Dashboard
1. Go to your Vercel project
2. Go to "Settings" → "Environment Variables"
3. Add new variable
4. Name: `MONGODB_URI`
5. Value: your connection string
6. Save

---

## Security Tips

- ⚠️ Never commit `.env` file to Git
- ✅ Use strong passwords in MongoDB connection strings
- ✅ Restrict MongoDB access by IP (in Atlas security settings)
- ✅ Use separate MongoDB users for each environment
- ✅ Rotate secrets regularly
- ✅ Don't share connection strings in code

---

## Troubleshooting MongoDB Connection

### "Connection Refused"
- MongoDB service not running
- Wrong host/port
- Firewall blocking connection

### "Authentication Failed"
- Wrong username/password
- User doesn't exist in MongoDB
- IP whitelist issue (Atlas)

### "Cannot Connect to MongoDB"
- Check MONGODB_URI in .env
- Verify MongoDB service is running
- Check network connectivity
- Try connecting with MongoDB Compass

---

## MongoDB Compass (GUI Tool)

To visually inspect your database:

1. Download MongoDB Compass: https://www.mongodb.com/products/compass
2. Use your MONGODB_URI to connect
3. Browse collections, add/edit data
4. Great for debugging

